summary.seg: The manuscript is an incomplete copy of the Strategemata of Polyaenus (2nd century CE). It was copied by Georgius Moschus in late 15th or early 16th century, and donated to the CUL by the bishop of London Cuthbert Tunstall (1474-1559): the donation note remains on f. [ii] recto. It later entered into the Wren Library from a donation of Thomas Nevile (ca. 1548-1615), Master of Trinity College (1593-1615).

A number of scholars have read the manuscript and one of them left a trace of the regret of not being able to read the whole text of Polyaenus: O factum male! (f. 94v). The royal librarian to King James VI and I, and King Charles I, Patrick Young (1584-1652), selected some variant reading from the Trinity College manuscript and they are now preserved in the manuscript
Leiden, Bibliotheek der Rijksuniversiteit, Voss. Misc. 8 , ff. 18r-24r. The manuscript was also used by Pancratius Maasvicius (1658-1719) for his edition (Leyden 1690).

supportDesc.collation:
The manuscript is tightly bound, but mapping the distribution of the watermarks is reasonable to assume that the manuscript consists of 10 quires:
Quires 1-910 ff. 1r-90v
Quire 106 ff. 91r-[iv] verso
A single signature in Greek numeral in brown ink survives on the upper right-hand corner of f. 71r, consistent with the collation: Ηʹ.

handNote.p: The manuscript was copied by Georgios Moschos (RGK I 67) active between the end of 15th and the beginnig of 16th century in a mixed minuscule script, slanting slightly to the right, in black ink, with modest variation in letter size.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings usually appear only at the end of lines, but occasionally elsewhere. Breathings are round and mute iota is used. Horizontal strokes appear over names.

The modern nu and sigma telikon are present. Enlarged lunate sigma wrap around the following letters. Beta appears in its bilobate shape, with the top loop smaller than the lower. The upper curve of minuscule delta is often extended obliquely.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, lower and middle commas and full stop.

history.origin:
The manuscript was copied by
Georgios Moschos Moschos, Georgios (RGK I 67; II 88; III 111). The combination of watermarks indicates that it was produced in late 15th or early 16th century.
history.acquisition:
Originally donated to the University Library by
Tunstall, Cuthbert, 1474-1559 Cuthbert Tunstall (1474-1559) , bishop of London, as recorded on f. [ii] recto: (Cuthebertus Londiniensis episcopus studiosis dono dedit). The manuscript was borrowed to Ascham, Roger, 1515-1568 Roger Ascham (1515-1568) by a Grace of the year 1539/40 (Luard 40). It was eventually donated to the Trinity College by
Thomas Nevile (ca. 1548-1615) Nevile, Thomas, -1615 , Dean of Canterbury (1597-1615), Master of Trinity College, Cambridge (1593-1615), during his mastership.
